@database "at3d.guide"



@Node MAIN "AccuTrans 3D Help"
                              AccuTrans 3D
                   @{" Program " link programs}, Manual, and On-Line Help
          Copyright (c) 1993 MicroMouse Productions, Regina, SK
                           All Rights Reserved

AccuTrans 3D transfers three dimensional object data between file formats.
The @{" basic operation " link basicOperation} of the program is quite easy.

Read and Write @{ "3D objects " link 3dObject} for:
     @{" AutoCAD DXF " link dxfObject} , @{" Imagine " link iObject} , @{" LightWave " link lwObject} , @{" VideoScape " link vsObject} , @{" Sculpt " link sObject}

AccuTrans 3D is divided into three sections:
     @{" Importing Data " link ImportData} , @{" Exporting Data " link ExportData} , @{" Preferences " link generalPrefs}

@{" Memory " link memory} allocation is dynamic.
@EndNode



@Node 3dObject "3D Objects"
Some method must be used to define a 3D object so that the computer can
draw it.  One method uses polygons and another uses mathematical equations
to describe the object.  @{" Imagine " link iObject}, @{" LightWave " link lwObject}, @{" VideoScape " link vsObject} and @{" Sculpt " link sObject}
use flat polygons to represent the surface of an object.  @{" AutoCAD " link dxfObject} uses
mathematical equations to represent an object.  A mathematical modeler will
accurately represent a curved surface whereas a polygon modeler will only
give an approximation of the curved surface.  For example, the polygon
based modelers use a group of points joined by straight line segments to
approximate a circle whereas @{" AutoCAD " link dxfObject} defines a perfect circle as a
center-point and a radius.

@{" Imagine " link iObject} and @{" Sculpt " link sObject} use triangles, three sided polygons.  The polygons
used by @{" LightWave " link lwObject} and @{" VideoScape " link vsObject} can have any number of sides.
A polygon is known as a face.  A triangle has one face, three edges and
three points which define the edges.  A point (also called a vertex in
@{" AutoCAD " link dxfObject}) is just a location in three dimensional space defined by
x, y, and z @{ "coordinates " link Coordinates}. An edge is a straight line segment defined by
two points.  A triangular face is defined as the three edges that make it
up.  AccuTrans 3D, @{" Imagine " link iObject} and @{" Sculpt " link sObject} use points and edges to define
a face.  @{" LightWave " link lwObject} and @{" VideoScape " link vsObject} use only points to define a face.

Imagine, Sculpt and LightWave files are Binary files.  VideoScape files are
ASCII files.  The program, Modeler 3D, also produces a VideoScape file that
is in Binary format.  AccuTrans 3D automatically determines whether a
VideoScape file is in @{" ASCII or Binary format " link asciiBinary} when it loads it.

If any 3D program, except for AutoCAD, does not define an object by points,
edges and faces than that object will not be loaded by AccuTrans 3D.
Imagine defines a perfect sphere and an infinite plane as special objects.
These special objects will not be translated by AccuTrans 3D.
@EndNode



@Node asciiBinary "ASCII and Binary Files"
Computers store information in files in either ASCII format or Binary
format.  Files that are in ASCII format can be read by any text editor.
ASCII files are also referred to as human-readable files.

  .   From an Amiga Shell, an ASCII file can be displayed to the screen by
      typing the command: type filename

  .   From an Amiga Shell, a Binary file can be displayed to the screen by
      typing the command:  type filename opt h
@EndNode



@Node Coordinates "3D Coordinates"
If you are designing solid three dimensional objects how are you going to
locate them in your world, space or universe?  The solution is to use a
x, y, z coordinate system.  The problem though is that the 3D programs do
not all use the same coordinate system.  Your computer monitor is the stage
on which you assemble all your actors (3D objects) for a performance.  The
coordinate system is defined according to this stage.  Moving from the left
to the right side of the monitor is moving in a positive x direction.
Moving from outside the monitor and into it is moving in the positive
y direction.  Moving from the bottom to the top of the monitor is moving
in the positive z direction.

AccuTrans 3D, AutoCAD, Imagine and Sculpt define the coordinate system this
way. Sculpt though does not show x, y, z coordinates on the screen.
Instead West to East compass direction is used for the x axis, South to
North for the y axis, and Down to Up for the z axis.

LightWave and VideoScape define the y and z axis directions differently.
Moving from out to in on the monitor is the z direction and moving from
the bottom to the top of the monitor is the y direction.  When AccuTrans 3D
reads or writes a LightWave or VideoScape file, it automatically flips the
y and z coordinates.
@EndNode



@Node dxfObject "AutoCAD DXF Objects"
AutoCAD is a general purpose Computer_Aided Design/Drafting program from
Autodesk, Inc.  This program is used to produce 2D and 3D drawings for many
applications such as aerospace, architecture, automobiles, and electronics.
AutoCAD  is not currently available for the Amiga computer but is available
for the PC-DOS, MS-DOS, OS/2, UNIX, AEGIS, VMS and Apple Macintosh
operating systems.  Other application programs needed to exchange data with
AutoCAD so Autodesk developed a Drawing Interchange File Format called DXF
to meet this need.  DXF files are standard @{" ASCII " link asciiBinary} text files.   The DXF
file standard is supported by many different programs including some CAD
programs on the Amiga.  A program may state that it reads, writes or
read/writes DXF files but it only gives partial support for the DXF format.
Before buying check that the program provides the support that you require.

See also: @{" DXF General File Structure " link dxfGeneral}
          @{" DXF File Creation          " link dxfCreate}
          @{" DXF BLOCKS Section         " link dxfBlocks}
          @{" DXF ENTITIES Section       " link dxfEntities}
          @{" Transferring DXF Files     " link dxfTransfer}
@EndNode



@Node dxfGeneral "DXF General File Structure"
The DXF file is simply an @{" ASCII " link asciiBinary} text file with the text formatted
according to a set of rules.  There are five sections in the file
structure.

   .   HEADER section contains general information about the drawing.
       AccuTrans 3D is not currently using any data from this section.

   .   TABLES section contains definitions for the following items:
       .   Linetype (LTYPE) table - AccuTrans 3D assumes that all lines are
           solid.
       .   LAYER table - AccuTrans 3D uses this table to obtain the layer
           name and its associated color.  This is the only table used by
           AccuTrans 3D.
       .   Text style (STYLE) table.
       .   View (VIEW) table.
       .   User Coordinate System (UCS) table.
       .   Viewport configuration (VPORT) table.
       .   Drawing manager (DWGMGR) table.

   .   @{" BLOCKS " link dxfBlocks} section contains information describing the entities used
       in each Block in the drawing.  AccuTrans 3D uses this section.

   .   @{" ENTITIES " link dxfEntities} section contains all the entities used in the drawing
       plus any included Block References.  AccuTrans 3D uses this section.

   .   EOF is the end of file marker.
@EndNode



@Node dxfCreate "DXF File Creation"
Many different programs create DXF format files.  Check the manual for the
program you are using for the appropriate command.  In @{" AutoCAD " link dxfObject} select
the DXFOUT command to create a DXF file.

   .   The default file name suggested will be the same as for the drawing
       but with the file extension changed to ".DXF".  If you choose a
       different file name it is suggested that you still use the file
       extension of ".DXF" for easier identification of the files later.

   .   If you are given the option of outputting a @{" Binary DXF " link asciiBinary} file, do
       not use it.  An @{" ASCII DXF " link asciiBinary} file is required.

   .   You will be prompted for the number of decimal places of accuracy to
       use for floating point numbers.  Six decimal places are suggested.
       If you choose no decimal places or too few decimal places then some
       parts of your drawing may not be translated and positioned
       accurately.

    .   Export the entire drawing to the DXF file.  If you only export the
        @{" ENTITIES " link dxfEntities} section, the color numbers used for the layers will be
        lost.  Also the @{" BLOCKS " link dxfBlocks} section is needed if your drawing used
        blocks.
@EndNode



@Node dxfCRLF "ASCII File Line Termination"
When an @{" ASCII " link asciiBinary} file is written one or two special characters are written
at the end of each line of text.  The special characters mark the end of
the line so that the computer knows how to handle the data when it reads
the file later.  Amiga and UNIX computers send just a line feed at the end
of a line of text.  The Macintosh computer sends just a carriage return and
an IBM PC computer sends a carriage return followed by a line feed.  There
is no need to worry about line termination when the file is read as
AccuTrans 3D automatically handles the combinations.  When a DXF file is
written by AccuTrans 3D you will be prompted for the type of line
termination to use.
@EndNode



@Node dxfBlocks "DXF BLOCKS Section"
Why use Blocks and what are they?

An @{" AutoCAD " link dxfObject} drawing consists of many @{" entities " link dxfEntities}, each of which is placed
at a certain @{" coordinate " link Coordinates} in the drawing.  One group of @{" entities " link dxfEntities} could
represent the 3D object of a chair while another group could represent a
desk. Assume you are designing a floor plan of a building with 20 offices
with one desk and three chairs in each office and you are not using blocks.
When the drawing is completed the client says that he wants to use a
different style of desk and chair.  You now have to delete and then redraw
20 desks and 60 chairs.  A lot of work but if you were using blocks you
would have only had to redraw one desk and one chair.

A Block is simply a grouping of all the @{" entities " link dxfEntities} required to make a
chair, or a desk, or an aileron on the wing of a plane, or a computer chip
on a circuit board, or a space station, or a what-ever.  Blocks can contain
other blocks and blocks can be rotated inside other blocks.  Blocks can be
as simple or as complicated as your needs require.  Use blocks to create a
custom library of parts that you want to use several times in one drawing
or in many drawings.  When you use a block in the main drawing AutoCAD
just makes a simple reference to the block in the @{" ENTITIES " link dxfEntities} section to
record its name, position, size and rotation.  This reduces the amount of
computer memory AutoCAD needs and the size of the disk file.  Then when
AutoCAD draws to the screen or plots to paper it references the data in the
BLOCKS section.

AutoCAD allows an external reference to Blocks where the actual block
information resides in another file.  AccuTrans 3D can only use blocks that
are included in the one DXF file.
@EndNode



@Node dxfEntities "DXF ENTITIES Section"
An AutoCAD drawing consists of many entities, each of which is placed at a
certain coordinate in the drawing.  An entity is a simple drawing element.
One entity could be a line joining two points, another could be a circle,
and another could be a four sided polygon. One group of entities could
represent the 3D object of an airplane wing while another group could
represent a flap on that wing.

   Entities NOT Supported
   .   Externally referenced data such as @{" Blocks " link dxfBlocks}.
   .   TEXT - text is externally referenced data.
   .   ATTDEF - used with TEXT.
   .   ATTRIB - used with TEXT.
   .   DIMENSION
   .   SHAPE  - it is more versatile and easier to use @{" Blocks " link dxfBlocks}.

   Entities Supported
   .   LINE
   .   CIRCLE
   .   ARC - number of points used can be varied for different arc sizes.
   .   TRACE
   .   SOLID
   .   BLOCK
   .   ENDBLK
   .   INSERT - name, insertion point, scale factor, rotation angle, column
       and row spacing and counts for Blocks are supported.
   .   POLYLINE - all features supported.
       .   simple polyline
       .   polylines with different starting and ending widths for each
           segment of the polyline.
       .   polylines that have been closed in any direction.
       .   polylines that have been curve-fitted or spline-fitted.
       .   polylines with bulges.
       .   3D POLYGON MESH - can be closed in any direction.
       .   3D POLYGON FACE - recommended that faces be made as triangles.
           The current algorithm may not properly decode polygons with more
           than 3 edges.
   .   VERTEX - used with POLYLINE
   .   SEQEND
   .   3DLINE
   .   3DFACE
@EndNode



@Node dxfTransfer "Transferring DXF Files"
DXF files produced on other makes of computer can be transferred to the
Amiga using MS-DOS formatted floppy disks, by 'null modem' cable or by
modem.

  .   On the IBM computer just copy the DXF file to a MS-DOS formatted
      floppy disk.  On the Macintosh use the Apple File Exchange utility
      (included with the system software) to copy the DXF file to a MS-DOS
      formatted floppy disk.  You will have to use floppy disks formatted
      for 720k bytes for the transfer unless your Amiga has high density
      floppy drives installed.  With high density floppies the disks can be
      formatted for 1.44 megabytes.  To read the DXF files from the MS-DOS
      disks on the Amiga use the CrossDOS utility which is supplied with
      Workbench 2.1 and higher.  If you do not have CrossDOS it can be
      purchased from its developer, Consultron.
                 Consultron
                 8959 Ridge Rd.
                 Plymouth, MI  48170-3213

  .   If the Amiga and the other computer are close to one another, they
      can be connected with a 'null modem' cable, which is just a serial
      cable.  Then with a telecommunication program running on both
      computers the DXF file can be transferred between the computers.  A
      communication protocol such as Xmodem or Zmodem should be used to
      ensure that no errors are created in the file during the transfer.

  .   If there is a large distance between the Amiga and the other
      computer, they can be connected by using modems over the telephone
      line and a telecommunications program running on both computers.  The
      computers can be connected by calling each other directly.  Another
      option is to upload the DXF file to a local BBS or to a national
      computer network.  At a later time the DXF file can be downloaded to
      the Amiga.

  .   Since DXF files are in @{" ASCII " link asciiBinary} format they can be quite large.  DXF
      files for buildings can range from 500k to at least 2 megabytes in
      size.  Reducing the size of the file will decrease the time required
      to transfer the file by either 'null modem' cable or modem.  Public
      domain and shareware file compression utilities such as Arc, LHarc,
      etc. are available for the Amiga, IBM and Macintosh computers. The
      same compression algorithm is not used by all the utilities.  Make
      sure that the program used for decompression is compatible with the
      program used for compressing the file.  The DXF files are
      human-readable files so a compression utility can usually decrease
      the file size by 20%.
@EndNode



@Node iObject "Imagine Objects"
Designing a complex object as one gigantic object is not always desirable.
Imagine allows you to design a complex object as a series of smaller
objects that are grouped together.  The objects are grouped in a
'hierarchy' which looks a lot like a 'family tree'.  This 'family tree'
resemblance creates parent - child  relationships.  Move a parent object
and all its children move also.  AccuTrans 3D supports this parent - child
relationship of objects.

Imagine allows the specification of @{" attributes " link Attributes"}, brush maps, textures,
etc. for every object.  AccuTrans 3D can assign many of these @{" attributes " link Attributes}
to an object.  Brush maps and textures are not assigned as the maps must be
aligned with an object axis and currently you can not view objects in
AccuTrans 3D.

Turbo Silver 3.0 (not the earlier versions) files are very similar to
Imagine files. AccuTrans 3D reads Turbo Silver 3.0 files. The Imagine
files written by AccuTrans 3D should load into Turbo Silver 3.0 but this
test has not been made.
@EndNode



@Node lwObject "LightWave Objects"
One object is stored per LightWave File.  If the object is complex, such as
a car, then the polygons making up the car are grouped according to their
@{" attributes " link Attributes}.  Each grouping of like polygons is called a surface. A car
could have surfaces for the tires, glass, body, lights, door handles, etc.
LightWave allows the specification of @{" attributes " link Attributes}, brush maps, textures,
etc. for every object.  AccuTrans 3D can assign many of these @{" attributes " link Attributes}
to an object but currently does not support brush maps and textures.

Spline based objects are supported in LightWave 3D included with the
Video Toaster 4000.  AccuTrans 3D does not currently support spline based
objects.
@EndNode



@Node vsObject "VideoScape Objects"
A VideoScape file can contain many objects such as several chairs and a
table with dishes on it.  When the file is viewed in VideoScape all the
objects can be seen but it is impossible to tell by looking at the file how
many objects are defined.  Therefore a VideoScape file is assumed to
contain only one object with many faces.  Each face is assigned a color
code number.  A VideoScape file can also define surface details for an
object. AccuTrans 3D ignores surface details when a file is read or
written.
@EndNode



@Node sObject "Sculpt Objects"
A Sculpt file can contain many objects such as several chairs and a table
with dishes on it.  When the file is viewed in Sculpt 3D all the objects
can be seen but it is impossible to tell by looking at the file how many
objects are defined.  Therefore a Sculpt file is assumed to contain only
one object with many faces.  Each face is assigned a RGB color.  In
addition to color, each face in a Sculpt file can have texture, which could
be dull, shiny, mirror, luminous or glass. This texture setting and also
the smoothing feature are currently ignored by AccuTrans 3D both when a
file is read or written.
@EndNode



@Node Attributes "3D Object Attributes"
Without attributes surfaces would have no character.  They would all look
the same.  Applying attributes, brush maps and textures can make surfaces
resemble a glass bottle, a marble floor, a granite wall, polished brass,
etc.  Attributes are a collection of characteristics such as color,
transparency, the way light is reflected or absorbed, roughness, etc.
For an explanation of how the attributes work refer to the manual that
came with your 3D Rendering program or a reference book such as
"Understanding Imagine 2.0" by Steve Worley.

AccuTrans 3D provides a window for each 3D program so that you can set the
attributes using slider and checkbox gadgets.  If you have favorite
attributes for Imagine and LightWave objects stored in disk files these can
be read in by AccuTrans 3D.

See also: @{" Common Attributes     " link commonAttributes}
          @{" Imagine Attributes    " link iAttributes}
          @{" LightWave Attributes  " link lwAttributes}
          @{" VideoScape Attributes " link vsAttributes}
@EndNode



@Node Font "Window and Text Size"
AccuTrans 3D opens its windows on the Workbench screen.  The Workbench can
be configured for different screen sizes, number of colors and size of the
text.  The Workbench parameters are adjusted by using the Preferences
programs located in the Prefs drawer on your System disk.  Currently
Workbench screen sizes are a minimum of 640 by 200 pixels.  The screen
colors can be from 2 to 16 colors.  The font sizes can be whatever size
that you have fonts for.  The screen text font adjusts the fonts used in
the top border of the window and for the menus.  The system default text is
used for the main part of the window and for the gadgets.

AccuTrans 3D was designed for a Workbench screen of 640 by 200 and
4 colors.  The default font expected is topaz 8 for both the screen text
and the system default text.  If you have decided to use fonts larger than
topaz 8 Accutrans 3D will adjust its window and gadget sizes to match.  If
the new window size will fit on the Workbench screen then AccuTrans 3D will
automatically use the larger fonts.

If the new window size required is larger than the Workbench screen size,
a requester will inform you of the size required.  Two choices for font
size are now available.  They are topaz 8 or the new Workbench font.  You
can choose topaz 8 and 'Continue' gadget and AccuTrans 3D will start.  If
you have made the screen size font larger than 8 then some windows will be
too large to be displayed on a 640 by 200 Workbench screen.  The other
choice is the 'Quit' gadget to exit AccuTrans 3D.  Then use the Preferences
programs to increase the size of the Workbench screen to at least the
required size.  Be sure to set the Workbench to AutoScroll if the window
size is larger than the displayable screen size for Workbench.  Now restart
Accutrans 3D.
@EndNode



@Node setColorPen "Pick Color Pen"
The windows for AccuTrans 3D were designed to open on the Workbench screen.
Currently the Workbench can be set to display from 2 to 16 colors.  When
the RGB color gadgets are shown for changing a color @{" attribute " link Attributes} one of
these Workbench colors must be temporarily changed to display the
@{" attribute " link Attributes} color.  Workbench uses color pens that are numbered from
0 to 15.  When AccuTrans 3D starts it selects Pen 1 for a 2 color screen
and Pen 3 for a 4 to 16 color screen.  With these selections the title
border of the window will change color when the RGB sliders are adjusted.
If more than 4 colors are used pick a pen with a number higher than 3 and
the title border will not change color.

@EndNode


@Node aslRequester "The ASL File Requester"
AccuTrans 3D uses the ASL file requester.  Starting with Version 2.0 of the
operating system, Commodore has included a standardized file requester that
works with asl.library located in the LIBS: drawer.  The file requester is
used to find the path and name for any file that you want the computer to
read or write.  Eventually all programs will probably use this file
requester.

Available in the Public Domain are file requester programs that replace the
ASL file requester.  If you are using one of these replacement programs on
your computer AccuTrans 3D will automatically use it also.
@EndNode



@Node filePatterns "Set File Patterns"
Whenever you click on a 'Read File' or 'Write File" gadget the AmigaDOS
@{" ASL file requester " link aslRequester} is displayed.  If you are using a custom replacement
ASL file requester then the replacement one will be displayed.  With this
file requester you can choose the file name and the path (drawer) to use to
find the file.  In addition a Pattern can be defined so that only drawers
and certain file names will be displayed.  For example if the drawer
contained both AutoCAD DXF files and other files and you set the
pattern #?.dxf then only the files ending in '.dxf' will be displayed.
#? are known as wildcard characters and for this example a file name with
any number of characters  preceding the .dxf  matches your request.  Using
patterns therefore greatly speeds up finding files in directories.
AccuTrans 3D allows you to set file matching patterns for importing and
exporting 3D objects, for @{" attribute " link Attributes} files and for preferences files.

If you make the pattern field blank (no letters displayed) or just enter
the wild card characters #? then all files in the directory will be
displayed.
@EndNode



@Node dxfColors "Set RGB Colors for DXF Layers"
Color numbers from 1 to 255 can be assigned as the color of any layer that
you create in AutoCAD.  This color number is used to define a RGB color
@{" attribute " link Attributes} for a 3D object.  The AutoCAD manual defines RGB values for
these 255 colors.  A default color table has been established using these
values. With this option you can set whatever RGB color you want for each
color number.  Since the RGB color is shown on the Workbench screen the RGB
value is shown as 0 to 255 but the actual color can only be shown in the
range of 0 to 15.

  .   A scrolling list of possible colors and their RGB values are provided
      to help you with your selection.  A single click on a color name will
      insert the values into the RGB sliders.
  .   Click on the 'Default Color' gadget to recall the color from the
      default color map.
  .   Click in the 'Reset' gadget to restore the color value that existed
      before you started editing.
  .   Click on 'Cancel' and all the current editing changes will be
      forgotten.
  .   Click on 'Okay' and all the current editing changes will be used.
@EndNode



@Node vsColors "Set RGB Colors For VideoScape Colors"
VideoScape uses a number code system for designating color.  The numbers
range from 0 to 63.  The 64 codes are divided into 16 colors in 4 sections
called matte, glossy, unshaded and unfilled outline.  With this option you
can set any RGB color for any number code.  Since the RGB color is shown on
the Workbench screen the RGB value is shown as 0 to 255 but the actual
color can only be shown in the range of  0 to 15.

  .   A scrolling list of possible colors and their RGB values are
      provided to help you with your selection.  A single click on a color
      name will insert the values into the RGB sliders.
  .   Click on the 'Default Color' gadget to recall the color from the
      default color map.
  .   Click in the 'Reset' gadget to restore the color value that existed
      before you started editing.
  .   Click on 'Cancel' and all the current editing changes will be
      forgotten.
  .   Click on 'Okay' and all the current editing changes will be used.
@EndNode



@Node infoIcon "Create Icon For Output File"
If this gadget is changed to 'Use Info Icon' then an icon (.info file) will
be created for the output file.
@EndNode



@Node basicOperation "Basic Operation"
The operation of this program is quite simple.
  .   Select the type of file to @{" read/import " link ImportData} by clicking on the cycle
      gadget until the correct file type is listed.
  .   Click on the @{" Read File " link readFile} gadget.
  .   Select the file to read using the displayed @{" file requester " link aslRequester}.
  .   Wait while the file is being read.
  .   Select the type of file to @{" save/export " link ExportData} by clicking on the cycle
      gadget until the correct file type is listed.
  .   Click on the @{" Write File " link writeFile} gadget.
  .   Select the file to write using the displayed @{" file requester " link aslRequester}.
  .   Wait until the file has been saved.
  .   Select the @{" Clear Memory " link clearMemory} gadget.
  .   Repeat the above instructions or @{" quit the program " link shutdown}.

Gadgets are used exclusively by this program.  The only menus are those
that are part of the System's @{" ASL file requester " link aslRequester}.  On-line help is
available by clicking on the 'Help' gadget displayed in each window or by
pressing the 'Help' key on the keyboard.
@EndNode



@Node shutdown "Program Shutdown"
To shutdown the program click on the CloseWindow gadget for the main
AccuTrans 3D window.  If memory is still filled with imported data, a
requester will ask if you want to clear the data.  A 'No' answer continues
program execution otherwise a 'Yes' answer clears memory and displays the
requester 'Do you want to save preferences'.  A 'Yes' answer will display
the file requester so you can choose a file name.  When AccuTrans 3D shuts
down it will also shutdown the program, @{" fixFloatAT3D " link programs}.
@EndNode



@Node programs "AccuTrans 3D Programs"
AccuTrans 3D is actually two programs. The main program is known as
AccuTrans 3D and the other is known as fixFloatAT3D. Both programs must be
located in the same directory. After AccuTrans 3D starts, it automatically
starts fixFloatAT3D. Then when AccuTrans 3D shuts down it also
automatically shuts down fixFloatAT3D.

AccuTrans 3D uses IEEE floating point math and fixFloatAT3D uses FFP
floating point math. The two programs communicate with each other to
handle conversions for the @{" Binary " link asciiBinary} VideoScape files used by Modeler 3D.
@EndNode



@Node ImportData "Importing Data"
The main window for the program shows general information, such as the
copyright, in the top box.  The next narrow and long box is used to display
messages at certain times.  The window is now divided into two boxes.  The
box on the left gives general instructions on how to import data.  The box
on the right contains all the gadgets to use for importing data.  The box
in the lower left contains the gadgets for handling the Layer Preferences
data.

Gadgets are:

   @{" Import ??? Data        " link inFileType}    @{" Set DXF Colors    " link dxfColors}   @{" ??? Preferences   "  link SelectPrefs}
   @{" Set Global Preferences " link Globals}    @{" Set VS Colors     " link vsColors}   @{" Load Preferences  " link LoadPrefs}
   @{" Set DXF Points Per Arc " link arcPoints}    @{" Pick Color Pen    " link setColorPen}   @{" Save Preferences  " link SavePrefs}
   @{" Input Scale Factor     " link inScaleFactor}    @{" No Info Icon      " link infoIcon}   @{" Edit Preferences  " link EditPrefs}
   @{" Read File              " link readFile}    @{" Set File Patterns " link filePatterns}   @{" Clear Preferences " link ClearPrefs}
@EndNode



@Node inFileType "Selecting Input File Type"
The type of file for import is chosen by clicking on the cycle gadget until
the desired file type is displayed.  Holding down the shift key when
clicking causes the cycle to go in the reverse direction.

Selecting the type of file for import is only required so that the correct
@{" file matching pattern " link filePatterns} can be selected for the @{" ASL file requester " link aslRequester}.
The file reader module used is actually a universal or smart file reader.
The file reader checks the file type when it starts to read the file and
will switch load modules, if necessary.
@EndNode



@Node Globals  "Set Global Preferences"
When a DXF file is decoded, for each @{" layer name " link objectNames} a data structure is
created and filled with the global preferences data.  The global
preferences data structure contains the @{" attributes " link Attributes} that will be used for
either an Imagine or a LightWave or a VideoScape object.  For example, if
all Imagine objects were to be set to QuickDraw then before any layers are
added and an object is imported set the global QuickDraw gadget to on.

See also @{" Global and Layer Preferences " link generalPrefs}
         @{" Global Preferences           " link GlobalPrefs}
@EndNode



@Node inScaleFactor  "Set Input Scale Factor"
AccuTrans 3D uses the double IEEE format for floating point numbers to
store all the @{" coordinates " link Coordinates} internally.  If the coordinates you input are
too large then use the input scale factor to reduce their magnitude. The
x, y, or z coordinates that are too large will not be detected until the
converted object is loaded into the 3D modeler.  You will either not see
an object because all coordinates are too large or polygons will be
stretched in the wrong directions and go off the screen.  If this is
observed it is probably because of a wrong output scale factor rather than
the input scale factor.
@EndNode



@Node arcPoints "Set Points Per Arc For DXF Files"
A DXF circle or an arc has to be approximated by a series of points joined
by straight line segments.  This option allows you to specify a different
number of points for arcs of different sizes.  If a certain size arc will
be zoomed in on for a closer look more points could be specified for that
arc.  For example, if you changed the 90° arc to 20 points than all arcs
from 46° to 90° would use 20 points when they were decoded.  The number of
points for any arc can be freely changed.  The 'Spread' gadget will evenly
proportion the designated points for the various arc sizes.  The 'Global'
gadget will set every arc increment to the same number of designated
points.
@EndNode



@Node readFile "Read File"
  .   When this gadget is selected an @{" ASL file requester " link aslRequester} is used to
      select the path and file name.

  .   As the file is being read the notice board section on the left
      changes to display the progress of the reading operation.  The count
      for Blocks, Entities and Vertex change as a DXF file is read.  The
      count for Vertices, Edges and Faces change when Imagine, LightWave,
      VideoScape and Sculpt files are read.

  .   The reading of the file can be aborted by clicking on the 'Cancel'
      gadget.

  .   When a DXF file is read the entities are grouped according to the
      @{" layer name " link objectNames}.

  .   Imagine objects are grouped in a parent - child relationship.  When
      the file is read one layer is created for each object in the
      hierarchy.  Parent - child relationships can take many possibilities.
      AccuTrans 3D does not keep track of all these possibilities, so do
      not import an Imagine file and then export the data as an Imagine
      file and expect the relationships to remain the same.

  .   One object with one or more surfaces is contained in a LightWave
      file.  When the file is read, one layer is created for each surface.

  .   A VideoScape file is assumed to be one object with the faces having
      one or more colors.  One layer is created for each unique color code
      in the file.  There is a possibility of 64 layers being created.  The
      VideoScape file format also defines surface details.  When the file
      is read these surface details are ignored.

  .   A Sculpt file is assumed to be one object with the faces having one
      or more colors.  @{" One surface is created for each color " link sculptSurfs}.
@EndNode



@Node sculptSurfs "Surfaces Created From a Sculpt Object"
A Sculpt object could contain 4096 unique colors.  After the Sculpt file is
read a requester will display the number of colors found in the file.  One
layer will be created for each color found.  If you do not want to create
that many layers enter a  smaller number.  For example, if 12 colors had
been found and you entered a request for 8, then colors 9 to 12 would be
read as color 8.  The colors are assigned numbers in the order found and
not by the number of faces containing that color.  Specifying fewer layers
could cause detail to be lost.  In addition to color, each face in a Sculpt
file can have texture, which could be dull, shiny, mirror, luminous or
glass.  This texture setting and also the smoothing feature are currently
ignored by AccuTrans 3D.
@EndNode



@Node memory "Memory Allocation"
When a 3D object file is read, computer memory must be allocated to hold
the data.  Both memory allocation and deallocation occur dynamically.  This
means that you do not have to tell the program how much memory to set aside
for its use.  Memory is allocated in small amounts and is taken first from
FAST memory and then from CHIP memory.  Whenever memory is allocated or
deallocated a counter in the lower right of the screen indicates that this
is happening.  When all memory has been used, a requester will inform you
of this.  After answering 'Okay' in the requester all memory used will be
cleared.  For DXF files the computer memory required is about 4 times the
size of the DXF file.  A 1 megabyte DXF file will require 4 megabytes of
memory.  If you do not have enough memory to translate the 3D object from
one format to another then there is also not enough memory to render the
picture.
@EndNode



@Node ExportData "Exporting Data"
The main window for the program shows general information, such as the
copyright, in the top box.  The next narrow and long box is used to display
messages at certain times.  The window is now divided into two boxes.  The
box on the left gives general instructions on how to export data.  The box
on the right contains all the gadgets to use for exporting data.  The box
in the lower left contains the gadgets for handling the Layer Preferences
data.

Gadgets are:
@{" Export ??? Data         " link outFileType}  @{" 1 VS Face         " link oneFace}  @{" ??? Preferences   " link SelectPrefs}
@{" Select Layers           " link selectLayers}  @{" Drawing As ???    " link dwgAs}  @{" Load Preferences  " link LoadPrefs}
@{" Select Blocks           " link selectBlocks}  @{" Write File        " link writeFile}  @{" Save Preferences  " link SavePrefs}
@{" Set Output Scale Factor " link outScaleFactor}  @{" Clear Memory      " link clearMemory}  @{" Edit Preferences  " link EditPrefs}
@{" Use Parent              " link useParent}  @{" No Info Icon      " link infoIcon}  @{" Clear Preferences " link ClearPrefs}
@{" No 2D                   " link no2D}  @{" Set File Patterns " link filePatterns}
@EndNode



@Node outFileType "Selecting Output File Type"
The type of file for export is chosen by clicking on the cycle gadget until
the desired file type is displayed.  Holding down the shift key when
clicking causes the cycle to go in the reverse direction.
@EndNode



@Node selectLayers "Selecting Layers"
Using this option AccuTrans 3D lets you select which layers should be
output for the new object.  When AccuTrans 3D first reads the file it
selects all layers for output.  Clicking on the gadget box either adds or
removes the checkmark.  Only those layers marked with a checkmark will be
output.

  .   An AutoCAD file creates one layer for every unique layer used in the
      BLOCKS and ENTITIES sections.

  .   An Imagine file creates one layer for each object in the
      parent - child hierarchy.

  .   A LightWave object is composed of one or more surfaces. A layer is
      created for each surface defined.

  .   A VideoScape object will use some combination of its 64 number codes.
      A layer will be created for each number code used.

  .   For Sculpt objects a layer will be created for each unique color
      found in the object.  The maximum layers created can be specified
      when a Sculpt file is read.
@EndNode



@Node selectBlocks "Selecting Blocks"
This option can only be used when an @{" AutoCAD " link dxfObject} file is imported.  In
addition the @{" BLOCKS " link dxfBlocks} section must be included in the @{" AutoCAD " link dxfObject} file and
the blocks must have been used in the drawing.  If a block was defined in
the @{" BLOCKS " link dxfBlocks} section but not actually used in the drawing, then the gadget
for that block will be ghosted.  This option works in two different ways.

  .   For Imagine output files: Whether a block is marked or not marked
      with a checkmark it will be written to the output file.  When the
      block is not marked it will become part of the object to which it
      belongs but when it is marked it will become a separate object.
      Assume that you have a wing designed that has two flaps on it.  The
      flaps were designed as a block but otherwise are on the same layer as
      the wing.  If the flap block is not checked then one object will be
      written to the output file.  The one object is the wing with the
      included flaps.  If the flap block was checked then three objects
      would be written to the file.  The objects are one wing and two
      flaps.

  .   For DXF, LightWave, VideoScape and Sculpt output files: If the gadget
      for the block is marked with a checkmark then it will be output to
      the file, otherwise it will not be output.  The output block will be
      part of the layer to which it belongs and will not be a separate
      entity.  Using the above wing example, if the block is checked you
       will get one object and will be able to see the flaps as part of the
       wing.  When the block is not checked the output file will show the
       wing with two holes where the flaps should have been.
@EndNode



@Node outScaleFactor "Setting Output Scale Factor"
  .   The box in the top left corner shows the minimum and maximum
      x, y, z values used in the vertices or points of the 3D model.  For
      a model from a DXF file there is the possibility of having both 2D
      and 3D entities present.  The gadget located in this box allows
      either for the inclusion or exclusion of 2D entities when
      calculating the minimum and maximum values.  2D entities can only be
      saved to Imagine files.

  .   The box in the lower left corner displays maximum values for the
      various 3D object formats.  Maximum Units is used for calculating
      the output scale factor.  Exceeding the values for objects, points,
      edges or faces would create an invalid file for the 3D
      modeler/rendering program.  If any of these values are exceeded you
      will be warned when you try to write the file and the operation will
      be aborted.  If the output scale factor causes a coordinate for a
      point to be invalid, a warning will not be given.  Published maximum
      values are not available for all formats so some numbers are educated
      guesses.  You can experiment with them.  For Imagine objects, if an
      object has two many points, edges or faces the object will be divided
      into as many sub-objects as needed.

  .   The box in the top right corner displays a cycle gadget to choose
      the type of output file and the output scale factor.  You can choose
      either a drawing scale factor or a manual scale factor.  The drawing
      scale factor applies the same factor to the x, y, and z @{" coordinates " link Coordinates}.
      The drawing scale factor is calculated by  dividing the Maximum Units
      by the absolute maximum x, y, or z component. Example is:
      
                 Minimum     Maximum    Measurement
                ----------  ----------  -----------
            X    1973.7376  18553.1341   16579.3965
            Y   10155.6629  30155.6629   20000.0000
            Z       0.0000  10500.0000   10500.0000
      
            Maximum Units: 100
            Drawing Scale Factor: = 100 / 20000 = 0.00500
      
      By changing the Maximum Units you can scale the object to any
      desired size. Choosing the manual scale factor allows for the same or
      different factor to be applied to the x, y and z @{" coordinates " link Coordinates}.
      The manual scale factor can even be negative.  The drawing scale
      factor will change when a new object is imported but the manual scale
      factor will remain the same.

  .   The box in the lower right corner displays an adjustment for the
      center point of the object.  LightWave and VideoScape objects are
      designed with the 0, 0, 0 @{" coordinate " link Coordinates} being at the approximate
      center of the object.  Click on the 'Calc' gadget and the center
      point of the object will be calculated.  You can use these values or
      change them.  If the 'Adjust Center Point' gadget is selected all
      @{" coordinates " link Coordinates} will be adjusted by the displayed amount when the
      object is exported.
      
      The manual states 'When a new object is loaded the center point is
      not automatically recalculated but remains at the old values'. This
      has been changed. When a new object is loaded if the
      'Adjust Center Point' gadget is selected and the 'Hold Center Point'
      gadget is not selected, a new center point is automatically
      calculated. If the 'Adjust Center Point' gadget is selected and the
      'Hold Center Point' gadget is selected, the center point remains the
      same. If the 'Adjust Center Point' gadget is not selected the center
      point is set to zero.
@EndNode



@Node writeFile "Write File"
  .   When this gadget is selected the @{" ASL file requester " link aslRequester} appears so that
      you can select the path and file name.  The program assumes that you
      will use the same path as on the last save (or the directory
      containing the AccuTrans 3D program if this is the first save). The
      file name will be the same as for the file just imported except the
      file name extension is changed to that specified by the export file
      pattern.

  .   Any layer that has been deselected will not be written to the export
      file.

  .   Imagine file: A hierarchy of objects is created with one object
      being created for each @{" layer name " link objectNames}. See also @{" Use Parent " link useParent},
      @{" No 2D " link no2D}, and @{" Drawing As ??? " link dwgAs}.

  .   LightWave file: One object is written to the file and this object
      will have as many surfaces as there are layers. See also @{" 1 VS Face " link oneFace}.

  .   VideoScape file: Before the file is written, a requester will ask if
      the file should be an ASCII or a Binary file.  One object is written
      to the file and each face will be assigned the VideoScape color code
      number assigned for that layer.  There will be as many colors as
      there are layers. See also @{" 1 VS Face " link oneFace}.

  .   Sculpt file: One object is written to the file and each face will be
      assigned the RGB color assigned to the layer.  There will be as many
      colors as there are layers.

  .   DXF file: Before the file is written a requester asks if only the
      ENTITIES section or both the TABLES and ENTITIES section should be
      written.  Also requested is the line termination characters to use.
      Carriage Return only for Macintosh files, Line Feed only for Amiga
      and UNIX files or a Carriage Return plus Line Feed for IBM PC files.
      The entities written will all be 3DFACES and each will be assigned to
      its layer.  If you do not save the TABLES section then AutoCAD will
      assign color 7 to every layer.
@EndNode



@Node useParent "Use Parent Gadget"
For Imagine only, if this gadget is selected a parent object, a cube, will
be created at the origin (0, 0, 0 coordinate).  The objects created from
each @{" layer name " link objectNames} will be linked to the cube.
@EndNode



@Node no2D "No 2D Gadget"
Select 'Use 2D' if you want to save both 2D and 3D objects to an Imagine
file only.
@EndNode



@Node oneFace "One VS Face Gadget"
LightWave and VideoScape polygons can be either visible or invisible.  For
a polygon to be visible the vertices of the polygon must be listed in a
clockwise order when the polygon is viewed from the visible side. Both the
LightWave and the VideoScape programs have a command to change the
visibility of any selected polygon.

Currently AccuTrans 3D does not determine if a polygon will be visible. If
you set the gadget to '1 VS Face' then the resulting object must be edited
in LightWave or VideoScape to make all faces visible. If the gadget is set
to '2 VS Faces' then the faces are output as both invisible and visible to
the file and the object will not have to be edited in LightWave or
VideoScape.
@EndNode



@Node dwgAS "Drawing as ??? Gadget"
For Imagine objects:

  .   Select 'Drawing as Layers' to save the entire drawing as one object
      per layer.

  .   Select 'Drawing as Layers and Blocks' to save the entire drawing as
      one object per layer plus any marked blocks will be removed from the
      parent layer and saved as a separate object on its own sub-layer.  If
      a block has its entities on 3 different layers then three new
      sub-layers will be created.

  .   Select 'Blocks only' and each block from the @{" BLOCKS " link dxfBlocks} section will be
      written to a separate file with the block's name used as the file
      name.  The path and file extension are taken from the
      @{ " ASL file requester " link aslRequester}. Even blocks that were not used in the
      @{" ENTITIES " link dxfEntities} section will be saved.  Scaling is not applied during this
      save.  Many custom blocks such as the trees, cars, chairs and tables
      that come with AutoCAD are designed based on one unit for each of the
      x, y, and z axes.
@EndNode



@Node abVS "Writing a VideoScape File"
Select ASCII output for a file that will be read by VideoScape.

Select either @{" ASCII or Binary " link asciiBinary} output for a file that will be
read by Modeler 3D.
@EndNode



@Node clearMemory "Clearing Memory"
Before you can import a new file, the computer memory must be cleared of
the old data.  If you select this gadget before you have saved the data
once the requester 'Do you want to ABANDON your work?' will be shown,
otherwise the requester will read 'Do you want to CLEAR your work'.
Select 'Yes' to clear the memory.

If object data is still in memory and has not been saved once and you click
on the CloseWindow gadget the above requester will display
'Do you want to ABANDON your work?'. Select 'Yes' and the program will end.
If the data has been saved once the requester will display
'End Program AT3D. Are You Sure?'. Select 'Yes' and the program will end.
@EndNode



@Node objectNames "Object Names"
3D objects can be assigned names.  Currently object names can not be edited
in AccuTrans 3D. 

  .   VideoScape and Sculpt files do not contain object names.  When these
      files are read the name assigned to the created Layer Preference data
      structure starts with either VS_ or Sculpt_ followed by a color
      number.  When a VideoScape or Sculpt file is written Layer Preference
      names are not written to the file.

  .   Names for Layers and Blocks in DXF files may be up to 31 characters
      long and may contain letters, digits, and the special characters
      "$" (dollar), "-" (hyphen), and "_" (underscore).  When a DXF file
      is written names are reduced to 31 characters if required.

  .   Names for objects in Imagine files may be up to 17 characters long.
      If any characters are illegal according to the DXF rules they are
      automatically changed.  When an Imagine file is written the names are
      reduced to 17 characters if required.

  .   Names for surfaces in LightWave files may be up to 79 characters
      long.  If any characters are illegal according to the DXF rules they
      are automatically changed.  When a LightWave file is written the
      names are reduced to 79 characters if required.
@EndNode



@Node generalPrefs "Global and Layer Preferences"
Preferences refers to the color and attributes associated with different
parts of the 3D object.

Three windows are used for both Global and Layer Preferences.  The three
windows for Global Preferences are the same as for Layer Preferences
except that they do not have the 'Default Clr' gadget, the 'Delete Forever'
gadget and from the top left corner the scrolling list of @{" layer names " link objectNames}
and the DXF layer color number (to the right of the label 'Layers').  The
definitions and the uses for the @{" attributes " link Attributes} listed in the windows will
not be discussed in this manual. Please refer to the manuals that were
supplied with the 3D programs or reference books on 3D objects.

See also: @{" Global Preferences " link GlobalPrefs}
          @{" Layer Preferences  " link LayerPrefs}
@EndNode



@Node GlobalPrefs  "Global Preferences"
Several parameters are set when a layer is defined in AutoCAD.  The only
parameters that AccuTrans 3D uses are the @{" layer name " link objectNames} and the color number
assigned to the layer.  When AccuTrans 3D imports a DXF file, every time a
new @{" layer name " link objectNames} is found a data structure is created which holds the layer
name, layer color number plus @{" attribute " link Attributes} information for Imagine and
LightWave and a color code number for VideoScape.  This newly created data
structure is filled with the values found in Global Preferences.

Why are global @{" attributes " link Attributes} needed?
When a complex object is constructed of many objects in Imagine or many
surfaces in LightWave there will be several attributes that will be common
to all or nearly all of the objects or surfaces.  If Phong shading and
QuickDraw are needed for all objects/surfaces check these in Global
Preferences and the computer presets the attributes for you as each layer
preference is created.

Each 3D program has defaults that it sets for any of its attributes.  When
a LightWave file is written by the LightWave program any attribute that is
set to the default value will not be written to the file. When AccuTrans 3D
reads a LightWave file it does not set the LightWave default value for any
attribute not found in the file but instead uses the AccuTrans 3D global
preferences value for  that attribute.
@EndNode



@Node LayerPrefs "Layer Preferences"
When a 3D object file is exported the @{" attributes " link Attributes} defined in Layer
Preferences will be written for every object/surface.  A Layer Preference
is created from the Global Preferences every time a new @{" layer name " link objectNames} is
read from the import file.  If a @{" layer name " link objectNames} already exists, when an
Imagine, LightWave, VideoScape or Sculpt file is read the new attributes
read will replace the attributes in the  existing preferences data
structure.  For a DXF file though the old attributes will be maintained.
All of the defined Layer Preferences can be saved to a data file.  If you
are revising a DXF project several times save the Layer Preferences to a
data file, and then reload these preferences before reading the revised DXF
file.

When working on several AutoCAD projects, you should choose layer names so
that the @{" layer name " link objectNames} will always have the same attributes associated with
the name.  If you always load and save Layer Preferences to the same
preferences file, then this file will eventually contain all your unique
layer names with their associated attributes.  Then when AccuTrans 3D
translates the DXF file all the attributes will be automatically set for
you.

If you do not clear the Layer Preferences data from computer memory between
importing different files then there will be both old and current layer
data.  When you edit Layer Preferences with object data in memory, the
scrolling list of @{" layer names " link objectNames} will only show the layer names associated
with the object currently loaded into memory.  When Layer Preferences is
edited with no object data in memory, then the scrolling list of layer
names will show all the layer names read since the computer memory was last
cleared of Layer Preferences.
@EndNode



@Node SelectPrefs "Select Preferences"
The cycle gadget selects the file type that will be used when the 'Edit'
gadget is clicked.
@EndNode



@Node LoadPrefs "Load Preferences"
When AccuTrans 3D is started it checks the current directory (the same
directory that contains AccuTrans 3D) for a preferences file named
AT3D.prefs.  If this file is found the global preferences, points per arc,
etc. plus any layer preferences will be loaded.

If the 'Load' gadget is not ghosted, clicking on this gadget will display
the @{" ASL file requester " link aslRequester}.  Select the preferences file to load.  The
preferences file can have any file name with any extension and be located
in any directory.
@EndNode



@Node SavePrefs "Save Preferences"
Clicking on the 'Save' gadget displays the ASL file requester.  The
preferences data can be saved to any file name with any extension and be
located in any directory.  A file extension of .prefs is suggested.

The gadget will be ghosted if there are currently no Layer Preferences in
memory.  Even if the gadget is ghosted when you quit AccuTrans 3D a
requester will be shown so that global preferences, points per arc, etc.
can be saved.
@EndNode



@Node EditPrefs "Edit Preferences"
Clicking on the 'Edit' gadget will display the @{" attributes " link Attributes} window for
Imagine, LightWave, or VideoScape.

See also @{" Global and Layer Preferences " link generalPrefs}
         @{" Global Preferences           " link GlobalPrefs}
         @{" Layer Preferences            " link LayerPrefs}
@EndNode



@Node ClearPrefs "Clear Preferences"
Clicking on the 'Clear' gadget will present the requester
'Clear PREFERENCES data?'.  Click on 'Yes' to clear the layer preferences
data only.  Global preferences, points per arc, etc. will not be cleared.
@EndNode



@Node commonAttributes "Common Attributes"
The windows for Imagine, LightWave and VideoScape attributes contain
gadgets that are common to all three windows.

  .   The attributes for any layer can be selected by clicking on a layer
      name located in the scrolling list gadget in the top left corner of
      the window.  The selected layer is listed in the box below the
      scrolling list.  The @{" layer names " link objectNames} can not be edited.

  .   The 'Load Attributes' gadget will display the ASL file requester.
      If you have favorite attributes, such as for a glass goblet or sheet
      of gold, you can select the Imagine or LightWave file containing
      them.

  .   The 'Delete Forever' gadget will delete the displayed layer forever.
      There is no undo button.

  .   The cycle gadget located below the 'Delete Forever' gadget will cycle
      the preferences from Imagine to LightWave to VideoScape.

  .   The RGB scrolling list gadget provides RGB values for many different
      colors.  Clicking on the color name will insert the values into the
      RGB sliders for Color, Reflect, Specular or Filter dependant on which
      one is currently selected.

  .   The Index of Refraction scrolling list gadget provides a list of
      Indices of Refraction for many different materials.  The Index of
      Refraction can be chosen by clicking on a name in the list or by
      selecting and then typing the desired index in the gadget box.

  .   Towards the top left corner is an unlabelled integer gadget.  For
      each layer in a DXF file a color number from 1 to 255 can be assigned
      to each layer.  This integer gadget is that color number.  Select the
      gadget and type in the required layer number.

  .   The 'Default Clr' gadget will change the RGB color to the values
      associated with the color number assigned to the DXF layer.
@EndNode



@Node iAttributes "Imagine Attributes"
Refer to the Imagine manual for an explanation of attributes for Imagine
objects.  The gadgets are either slider gadgets or checkbox gadgets.
@EndNode



@Node lwAttributes "LightWave Attributes"
Refer to the LightWave manual for an explanation of attributes for
LightWave objects.  The gadgets are either slider gadgets or checkbox
gadgets.
@EndNode



@Node vsAttributes "VideoScape Attributes"
VideoScape objects set color code values instead of RGB values for the
color of each polygon.  There are four sets of colors with sixteen colors
in each set.  The sets are called matte, glossy, unshaded and unfilled
outline.

The RGB color slider values are not saved to a VideoScape file.  They are
only displayed here for a reference when setting the color code.  The color
code can be set by typing in the required number in the integer gadget or
by setting the color code with the cycle gadget and then selecting the
color from the 16 color names displayed.
@EndNode
